03775nam a22005415i 9780822394471DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223944717 a10.1515/97808223944712doi  a(DE-B1597)553956  a(OCoLC)1125525363  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aB2430.B274 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a320.0921 aBosteels, Bruno, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBadiou and Politics /cBruno Bosteels. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (464 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Elements of Dialectical Materialism -- t1. The Absent Cause -- t2. Lack and Destruction -- t3. One Divides into Two -- t4. The Ontological Impasse -- t5. Forcing the Truth -- t6. Logics of Change -- t7. From Potentiality to Inexistence -- t8. For Lack of Politics -- tConclusion. The Speculative Left -- tIn dialogue with Alain Badiou -- tAppendix 1. Can Change Be Thought? -- tAppendix 2. Beyond Formalization -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBadiou and Politics offers a much-anticipated interpretation of the work of the influential French philosopher Alain Badiou. Countering ideas of the philosopher as a dogmatic, absolutist, or even mystical thinker enthralled by the force of the event as a radical break, Bruno Bosteels reveals Badiou's deep and ongoing investment in the dialectic. Bosteels draws on all of Badiou's writings, from the philosopher's student days in the 1960s to the present, as well as on Badiou's exchanges with other thinkers, from his avowed "masters" Louis Althusser and Jacques Lacan, to interlocutors including Gilles Deleuze, Slavoj Žižek, Daniel Bensaïd, Jacques Derrida, Ernesto Laclau, and Judith Butler. Bosteels tracks the philosopher's political activities from the events of May 1968 through his embrace of Maoism and the work he has done since the 1980s, helping to mobilize France's illegal immigrants or sans-papiers. Ultimately, Bosteels argues for understanding Badiou's thought as a revival of dialectical materialism, and he illuminates the philosopher's understanding of the task of theory: to define a conceptual space for thinking emancipatory politics in the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394471zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394471423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394471.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles